      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "880953a1d25335ac",
        "text": "If one analyses from a greater distance, it becomes apparent that those conceptual problems of social theory were unsolvable for m ultiple reasons, which stabilize each other. (1) For plausible reasons, the view that the whole is more than the sum of the parts had been accepted, although social theories of the kind outlined would have given reason to accept the opposite thesis and to say that the whole is less than the sum of the parts, that it is order as a reductive achievement. As is understandable in certain evolutionary situations of fascinating novelty, (2) society as a whole was characterized by features of its most important subsystem and its concept was thereby concretized - first as a political, then as an economic society. T hrough this, the whole remained infected with characteristics that could not be representative of the totality of the items subsumed under it. Two-valued logic was seen (3) not only as a limited functionally adequate schematism, but as a reflection of a real difference between being and non-being, and as a result (4) neither self-referential processes nor intersubjectivity, nor systems with a structurally immanent reference to the environment, nor systems with a structurally immanent reference to time could be conceived. And (5) no sufficient distinction was made between different levels of system formation, above all between the social system and organized social systems, and as a result a pars pro toto technique, which is easily possible in organizations, was transferred to the social system presented as a corporation. All these options are understandable from the historical situations and evolutionary perspectives of past social systems. In all these respects, one could judge differently today."
      },
