        "text": "The main difference that separates us from the beginnings of sociology and the social theories of the 19th century, i.e. also from Marx's theory, lies in the systems theory approach. This is not just a specific, competing version of social theory. If one starts from a theory of social systems, one analyzes from a conceptual level that is more aggregated than the theory of society. Sociology is then no longer just social theory (or, as in the Eastern Bloc, an empirical auxiliary science of social theory). For them, the theory of the comprehensive system of social reality is only a partial theory. In other words, sociology needs a different, more abstract level of meaning to integrate its findings than society needs to integrate itself. As the sketch should make clear, a distinction must therefore be made between the theoretical (analytical) and the social (real) relations of inclusion, even though sociology can understand itself as a subsystem of society."
